-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_EXPR_METHOD_CALL.
--
-- # KNOWN GAP: super.method() dispatch lands in a future phase (super
--              wiring). Iron v0.1.4-alpha parses the `super` keyword
--              but typecheck does not wire method-on-parent-type
--              lookup (see Phase 66-03 PROT-04 rewrites where the
--              super handler in resolve.c had to blind-cast to
--              Iron_ObjectDecl). This canary exercises direct
--              instance-method dispatch on an object without
--              inheritance, which is the subset supported today.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because of a locally-
-- shadowed struct typedef. Method-call dispatch is especially risky
-- because it carries a receiver expression plus an argument list,
-- and the HIR walker must recurse into both -- plus the method name
-- resolves at lower_expr time via the object's resolved type. Walker
-- cases that handle METHOD_CALL but mis-recurse into the receiver or
-- arg list silently drop sub-expressions from the lowered LIR.
-- Phase 66 added PROT-04 blind-cast fixes for method-call sites
-- (see tests/integration/bug_audit_heap_method_call.iron) and
-- -Werror=switch-enum; this canary is the per-node-kind regression
-- net for the METHOD_CALL dispatch path.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_MethodCallExpr carries
--   { span, kind, receiver, method_name, args[], arg_count,
--     resolved_target, resolved_type }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into `receiver` drop the
-- callee's object; cases that skip args[] drop method parameters;
-- cases that ignore resolved_target mis-dispatch at codegen time.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Exercises instance-method dispatch on an extends-less
-- object (the subset supported today). super.method() is documented
-- as a KNOWN GAP in the header above and tracked for a future phase.
-- CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's
-- build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- method calls are the
-- dominant expression form in object-oriented Iron code, so any
-- walker regression would produce silently wrong output on every
-- typical program.

object Counter {
  var value: Int
    init(value: Int) {
        self.value = value
    }
}

func Counter.bump() -> Int {
  return self.value + 1
}

func Counter.triple() -> Int {
  return self.value * 3
}

func Counter.add(x: Int) -> Int {
  return self.value + x
}

func main() {
  val c = Counter(10)
  println("bump: {c.bump()}")      -- 11
  println("triple: {c.triple()}")  -- 30
  println("add: {c.add(7)}")       -- 17
}
